{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638119","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638119"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:49:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:49:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17689"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17689"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10403"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72062"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10403"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17689"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57532"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7504"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24314"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24349"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72062","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72062"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe vestibular system contains specialised structures that help maintain balance and spatial orientation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of the saccule?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Detects sound waves in the middle ear","Detects rotational head movements","Detects changes in endolymph pressure","Detects linear acceleration in the vertical plane","Detects horizontal linear acceleration"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esaccule detects linear acceleration in the vertical plane\u003C/strong\u003E and static head position relative to gravity. It contains hair cells embedded in an otolithic membrane with calcium carbonate crystals that move in response to gravitational forces and vertical acceleration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetection of sound waves in the middle ear\u003C/strong\u003E is performed by the tympanic membrane and ossicles, which transmit sound vibrations to the inner ear.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetection of rotational head movements\u003C/strong\u003E is the function of the semicircular canals, which contain endolymph that moves in response to angular acceleration.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetection of changes in endolymph pressure\u003C/strong\u003E is not a primary sensory function in the vestibular system, though endolymph movement is important for hair cell stimulation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetection of horizontal linear acceleration\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily performed by the utricle, which contains hair cells oriented in the horizontal plane.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe saccule, along with the utricle, forms the otolithic organs of the vestibular system. These structures are essential for maintaining balance and spatial orientation by detecting linear accelerations and head position relative to gravity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The saccule detects linear acceleration in the vertical plane and static head position relative to gravity.","The saccule contains hair cells embedded in otolithic membrane with calcium carbonate crystals that respond to gravitational forces.","The saccule is located in the vestibular system of the inner ear and contributes to balance and spatial orientation."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57532"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17689"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57532"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T22:12:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T22:13:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10403"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72062"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/ap